J. B. Rainsberger wrote:

&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;public void testSomeClasspathVariation() {
&gt;&gt;           
&gt;&gt;  ClasspathWalker walker = new ClasspathWalker();
&gt;&gt;  MockClasspathWalkerListener listener =
&gt;&gt;      new MockClasspathWalkerListener();
&gt;&gt;  walker.addListener(listener);
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;  walker.walkClasspath(someClasspathVariation)
&gt;&gt;           
&gt;&gt;  assertTrue(listener.heard(someExpectedEvent));
&gt;&gt;}
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; I assumed that each different classpath variation gave rise to a collection of events, 
&gt; possibly diverse ones. That&#39;s why I jumped to the more granular tests. If each classpath 
&gt; variation maps to a single event, then there&#39;d be no need to test &quot;when I find this I 
&gt; generate that event&quot; and it collapses to the above.
&gt; 

I also assumed I&#39;d want to test for a collection of events.  I&#39;d just 
use something like:

   assertTrue(listener.heard(firstExpectedEvent));
   assertTrue(listener.heard(secondExpectedEvent));
   assertTrue(listener.heard(thirdExpectedEvent));

Each test method would test a different variation of the classpath, and 
thus could expect different, and multiple, events.

I&#39;m not saying this is THE way, it&#39;s just a way that has worked for me. 
  More and more I&#39;m writing tests to verify behavior, not 
classes/methods, and this approach is the first thing that comes to mind.

